        + p9.labs(x ='Income',

                  fill ='World Regions',

Part 4: What other geometries could you use here besides geom_point? Provide an actual plot of another geometry being used here and why itâs good or bad for visualizing these data.

Another geometry that can be used other than geom_point is the line plot style-geometry which I used below. After viewing the dataset and our variables,âincomeâ, âlife_expâ, âfour_regionsâ, and âpopulationâ, I think a scatterplot is more suitable to visualize the relationship between income and life expectancy, which are both continuous variables since, scatterplots are meant especially for this purpose and with added aesthetics like filled color for regions and size for population, they can help better represent multi-dimensional data. A line plot might also be suitable if we wanted to observe the trend over a certain period of time between the two variables or the data had a time series format as seen in the visualization below.

#Creating the line plot and storing it in a object
line_plot = (p9.ggplot(df_q1, mapping = p9.aes(x='income', y='life_exp', color='four_regions'))

             # Annotations specified to add text to the geometry
             + p9.annotate("text", x = 180000, y = 15, label ="per person(GDP/capita, PPP$ inflation-adjusted)", color = "grey", size = 10, ha = "right")
             + p9.annotate("text", x = 500, y = 88, label = "years", color ="grey", size = 10, ha = "right", angle = 90)
             + p9.annotate("text", x = 8000, y = 50, label = "2010", color = "grey", size = 190, alpha = 0.2)
             + p9.annotate("text", x = 1900, y = 90, label = "INCOME LEVEL 1", color = "grey", size = 10, ha = "right")
             + p9.annotate("text", x = 5700, y = 90, label = "LEVEL 2", color = "grey", size = 10, ha = "right")
             + p9.annotate("text", x = 16000, y = 90, label = "LEVEL 3", color = "grey", size = 10, ha = "right")
             + p9.annotate("text", x = 51000, y = 90, label = "LEVEL 4", color = "grey", size = 10, ha = "right")

             # Line plot with size defined for thickness of plot
             + p9.geom_line(size = 1.5)

             # Labels of axes and legend
             + p9.labs(x ='Income', y ='Life expectancy', color ='World Regions')
             + p9.guides(color = p9.guide_legend(title = "World Regions"))


             # Themes and colors specified as well as labels of legend capitalized
             + p9.theme_bw()
             + p9.theme(text = p9.element_text(size = 14), figure_size = (12, 6))
             + p9.scale_color_manual(values = {"africa": "aqua","asia": "salmon","americas": "lawngreen", "europe": "yellow"},
                                     labels = {"africa": "Africa", "asia": "Asia", "americas": "Americas", "europe": "Europe"})

             # Breaks and labels pf x and y axes
             + p9.scale_x_continuous(breaks = [500, 1000, 2000, 4000, 8000, 16000, 32000, 64000],
                                     labels = ["500", "1000", "2000", "4000", "8000", "16k", "32k", "64k"],
                                     trans = 'log', limits = (500, 180000))
             + p9.scale_y_continuous(breaks = [20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90],
                                     labels = ["20", "30", "40", "50", "60", "70", "80", "90"], limits = (15,90)))

#print/display the lineplot
print(line_plot)

Part 4: What other geometries could you use here besides geom_point? Provide an actual plot of another geometry being used here and why itâs good or bad for visualizing these data.

Another geometry that can be used other than geom_point is the box plot style-geometry which I used below. After viewing the dataset and our variables,âexportsâ, âimportsâ, âfour_regionsâ, and âenergyâ, I think it really depends on what exactly we want to provide insights on. The scatterplot is more suitable to visualize the relationship between exports and imports, which are both continuous variables since, you can clearly see the trend and correlation in these two variables and since scatterplots are meant especially for this purpose and with added aesthetics like filled color for regions and size for population, they can help better represent multi-dimensional data. A boc plot might also be suitable if we wanted to observe the distribution between the two variables - exports and imports across different categories. However the disadvanatge with using a boxplot to visualize data is that specific data points are not displayed unless they are outliers. You canât see the exact relationship between exports and imports for each category.

#Creating the boxplot and storing it in a object
box_plot2 = (p9.ggplot(df_q2, mapping = p9.aes(x='exports', y='imports', fill ='four_regions', size ='energy'))

        + p9.geom_boxplot(alpha = 1)

        # Annotations, Labels, Themes ,Guide and color specified to enhance visualization
        + p9.annotate("text", x = 115, y = 175, label = "1997", color = "grey", size = 205, alpha = 0.2)
        + p9.labs(x ='Exports(\% of GDP)', y ='Imports(\% of GDP)', fill ='World Regions', size ='Energy Use')
        + p9.theme_bw()
        + p9.theme(text = p9.element_text(size = 12), figure_size = (12, 6))
        + p9.guides(size = False, fill = p9.guide_legend(title = "World Regions"))
        + p9.scale_fill_manual(values = {"africa": "aqua", "asia": "salmon", "americas": "lawngreen", "europe": "yellow"},
                               labels = {"africa": "Africa", "asia": "Asia", "americas": "Americas", "europe": "Europe"})

        #Breaks and Labels for the axes
        + p9.scale_x_continuous(breaks = [20, 40, 60, 80, 100, 120, 140, 160, 180, 200, 220],
                                labels = ["20", "40", "60", "80", "100", "120", "140", "160", "180", "200", "220"],
                                 limits = (0,220))
        + p9.scale_y_continuous(breaks = [50, 100, 150, 200, 250, 300, 350, 400],
                                labels = ["50", "100", "150", "200", "250", "300", "350", "400"], limits = (0,400)))

#print/display boxplot created
print(box_plot2)

        + p9.geom_point(alpha = 1)

        # Annotations specified to add text to the geometry
        + p9.annotate("text", x = 105, y = 100, label ="\% of population", color = "grey", size = 10, ha = "right")

        + p9.theme_bw()
        + p9.theme(text = p9.element_text(size = 12), figure_size = (12, 6))
        + p9.guides(size = False, fill = p9.guide_legend(title = "World Regions"))
        + p9.scale_fill_manual(values = {"africa": "aqua", "asia": "salmon", "americas": "lawngreen", "europe": "yellow"},
                               labels = {"africa": "Africa", "asia": "Asia", "americas": "Americas", "europe": "Europe"})
        + p9.scale_size(range=(1, 13))

        # Breaks and Labels specified for each axis
        + p9.scale_x_continuous(breaks = [10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90],
                                labels = ["10", "20", "30", "40", "50", "60", "70", "80", "90"],
                                 limits = (0,110))
        + p9.scale_y_continuous(breaks = [200, 500, 1000, 2000, 5000, 10000, 20000, 50000,100000],

Part 4: What other geometries could you use here besides geom_point? Provide an actual plot of another geometry being used here and why itâs good or bad for visualizing these data.

Another geometry that can be used other than geom_point is the violin plot style-geometry which I used below. After viewing the dataset and our variables,âinternet_usersâ, âgdpâ, and âincomeâ, I think a scatterplot would be a better visualization of the data rather than the violin plot. The scatterplot is more suitable to visualize the relationship between GDP and internet users across countries, which are both continuous variables since, you can clearly see the trend and correlation in these two variables and since scatterplots are meant especially for this purpose and with added aesthetics like filled color for regions and size for population, they can help better represent multi-dimensional data. A violinplot is not suitable if we wanted it to effectively, provide insight into the relationship between two continuous variables. Also compared to a scatterplot, 2 or more variables are less intuitively displayed and represented than in a scatterplot.

warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')

#Creating the violinplot and storing it in a object
violin_plot3 = (p9.ggplot(df_q3, p9.aes(x='internet_users', y='gdp', fill ='four_regions', size = 'income'))
    + p9.geom_violin(alpha = 0.5, width = 5)

    # Annotations specified to add text to the geometry
    + p9.annotate("text", x = 105, y = 40, label ="\% of population", color = "grey", size = 10, ha = "right", va = "center")
    + p9.annotate("text", x = 0, y = 40000, label = "US$, inflation-adjusted", color ="grey", size = 10, ha = "right", angle = 90)
    + p9.annotate("text", x = 48, y = 3200, label = "2001", color = "grey", size = 140, alpha = 0.2)

    # Labels, Themes, Guide and color specified to enhance visualization
    + p9.labs(x='Individuals using the Internet', y='GDP/capita', fill='World Regions')
    + p9.theme_bw()
    + p9.theme(text = p9.element_text(size = 12), figure_size = (12, 6))
    + p9.scale_fill_manual(values = {"africa": "aqua", "asia": "salmon", "americas": "lawngreen", "europe": "yellow"},
                           labels = {"africa": "Africa", "asia": "Asia", "americas": "Americas", "europe": "Europe"})

    # Breaks and Labels specified for each axis
    + p9.scale_x_continuous(breaks = [10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90],
                            labels = ["10", "20", "30", "40", "50", "60", "70", "80", "90"],
                            limits = (0,110))

    + p9.scale_y_continuous(breaks = [200, 500, 1000, 2000, 5000, 10000, 20000, 50000,100000],
                            labels = ["200", "500", "1000", "2000", "5000", "10k", "20k", "50k", "100k"],
                            trans = 'log'))
#print/display violinplot created
print(violin_plot3)
